Plum's stage or Mei's stage
London faces Theresa May, the newly appointed UK Prime Minister, with a daunting task: to implement the "withdrawal from the EU" demand made by British voters, or more accurately, English and Welsh voters, and manage the far-reaching consequences of this effort.
This challenge she faces dwarfs her predecessors in recent years.
But she may be able to complete this task.
No one should underestimate Mori.
Like German Chancellor Merkel, who has already proven her courage in a series of crises, all the tools needed to complete the task are in Xi's hands.
She is intelligent and persistent, and has no patience for nonsense.
She possesses a strong sense of public service and equally strong values.
She is not constrained by any ideology, very skilled at controlling power, and operates within the self-defined boundaries, to ensure familiarity with the issues being dealt with.
Plume won most of the battles she participated in, showing no mercy to those who had previously tried to deal with her unfairly.
But she had few enemies within the party and was quite popular among ordinary party members.
This is a powerful combination — she needs to harness it to lead Britain out of the Brexit process.
The British withdrawal process has already begun, this is undeniable.
Even if Scotland and Northern Ireland vote to remain in Europe, Brexit cannot be reversed.
She repeatedly emphasized "Brexit means Brexit," and her cabinet ministers all agreed with her stance.
However, May has not yet provided a precise definition of Brexit.
This task is very difficult to complete.
Just imagine someone telling you, 'Breakfast is just breakfast,' and then starts preparing food for you.
You have no idea what you'll really get.
A full Northern Irish "Ulster fry" – an egg, bacon, sausage, black pudding, potatoes, soda bread and fried tomato – with a cup of tea?
Coffee and cakes?
Depending on the environment you are in and your personal preferences, you may feel differently about various possible combinations.
The same situation also applies to Brexit.
Some people may mainly be concerned with preventing EU labor from entering the UK.
Some people are even more concerned about obtaining single market access.
Unlike breakfast, in the UK, you cannot order a single portion of each dish on the menu.
The reality often overlooked by the Brexit camp is that the EU will not give the UK a free ride.
This is not because EU leaders want to win over public opinion or punish the UK for refusing the EU (such inflammatory rhetoric sometimes makes the rounds, like the "Hitler-esque imperialism" phrase used by UK's new Foreign Secretary Boris Johnson).
On the contrary, we Britons often forget that everyone - including the EU and all its member states - has their own political or commercial interests to uphold.
For Ms Raab, the core challenge over the coming months will be to determine what Britain's objectives should be after the arduous negotiations on a new relationship with the EU (and, in the trade context, the world at large) have begun on a firm foundation in reality.
Considering the scope of the agenda (I can think of at least six major topics that require separate negotiations), the negotiation process may take several years to complete.
When the negotiation is completed, my 11-year-old granddaughter may already be in college!
We must clarify the priority in order to prevent the negotiation from taking longer.
The ultimate goal is to balance goods and services exports from the UK (particularly financial services) into the rest of Europe and restrictions on the free movement of EU citizens into the UK.
The more concessions one gains in one area, the more concessions one must make in another.
Mai needs to fully utilize her knowledge, skills, and political capital to ensure the reasonableness of the negotiation transaction.
Even if she succeeded in achieving her goal, she would still find that not only a part of them - such a result is inevitable - but all of them are dissatisfied.
This will exacerbate another major challenge facing the May government: the widening of the growing social divide in Britain exposed by Brexit.
Working-class people in northern and mid-England were the driving force behind the UK's Brexit vote, having long felt disconnected from the political elite, left behind by globalization, and marginalised by the supposed proxy - the European Union.
Urban England — especially London — may benefit greatly from globalization, but they have not received any benefits.
Lacking confidence in Jeremy Corbyn's leadership of the Labour party, many of the blue-collar working class became prey to the Brexit populist promise.
"They say they will reverse globalization."
"We will drive out low-wage immigrants and transfer hundreds of millions of pounds originally given to the EU to public services."
They promise that Brexit will allow Britain to relive a safer and more prosperous past.
Brexit supporters cannot truly deliver on these commitments.
Globalization is irreversible, nor can it cut off immigration from the European Union.
Any such move would only ruin British businesses.
Even if economic downturn leads to a decline in migration, those workers who voted for Britain's exit from the EU may still be disheartened to find that low-paying jobs remain low-paying and that pressure on public services remains heavy.
This is unlikely to lead to an increase in social cohesion.
The Brexit referendum has unleashed a populist storm that is difficult to control.
Like Donald Trump was unable to improve the lot of wage-earning voters in the United States, Brexit is also completely unable to bring benefits to those who chose it.
Despite having numerous advantages, such a challenge may still be too great for Me to overcome.
